VALUES
(42, 11, 53, 42, 20, 20, 20, 'urge him vehemently', 'Opposition to Jesus'' Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility of the scribes and Pharisees towards Jesus. In Luke 11:53, they provoke him to speak, while in Luke 20:20, they watch him closely to trap his words.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 53, 42, 20, 27, 27, 'urge him vehemently', 'Opposition to Jesus'' Teachings', 'This connection highlights the ongoing challenge Jesus faced from religious leaders. In both passages, the scribes, Pharisees, and Sadducees are depicted as actively provoking Jesus regarding his teachings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 53, 46, 13, 5, 5, 'to provoke him to speak of many things', 'Provocation and Behavior', 'This connection highlights the theme of provocation in both passages. In Luke 11:53, the scribes and Pharisees provoke Jesus, while 1 Corinthians 13:5 describes a behavior that is ''not easily provoked.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 41, 12, 13, 13, 'catch something out of his mouth', 'Attempts to Trap Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the efforts of religious leaders to catch Jesus in his words, highlighting their intent to accuse him. The phrases ''laying wait for him'' and ''to catch him in his words'' illustrate a shared theme of entrapment.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 40, 22, 15, 15, 'laying wait for him', 'Entanglement in Speech', 'Both passages emphasize the intent to catch Jesus in his words. The phrase ''laying wait for him'' in Luke parallels the Pharisees'' strategy to ''entangle him in his talk'' in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 40, 22, 35, 35, 'seeking to catch something out of his mouth', 'Temptation and Accusation', 'Both passages emphasize the act of questioning Jesus with the intent to trap him. In Luke, the focus is on laying wait to catch him, while in Matthew, the lawyer''s question is described as tempting him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 19, 37, 32, 33, 'laying wait for him', 'Wickedness and Righteousness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the wicked''s intent to harm the righteous. In Luke, the wicked lay in wait to accuse, while in Psalms, they seek to slay the righteous. This connection highlights the persistent threat faced by the righteous from the wicked.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 19, 56, 5, 6, 'laying wait for him', 'Words and Accusation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals plotting against the speaker by misusing their words. Both passages emphasize the act of waiting and seeking to catch the speaker in a moment of vulnerability.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 42, 20, 20, 20, 'catch something out of his mouth', 'Plot Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of those who sought to catch Jesus in his words. They illustrate a persistent effort to accuse him and deliver him to authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 54, 41, 3, 2, 2, 'that they might accuse him', 'Accusation Motif in Gospels', 'Both passages emphasize the intent to accuse Jesus. In Luke, they are ''laying wait for him,'' while in Mark, they are ''watching him'' for a similar purpose. This connection highlights the ongoing scrutiny Jesus faced from his opponents.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 60, 2, 1, 1, 'leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy', 'Connection of Hypocrisy Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy present in both passages. Luke warns against the ''leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy,'' while Peter instructs to lay aside ''hypocrisies'' among other vices.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 46, 5, 7, 8, 'leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy', 'Connection of Leaven and Hypocrisy', 'This connection highlights the theme of leaven as a metaphor for corruption. Both passages emphasize the need to purge out negative influences, whether it be hypocrisy or malice, to maintain spiritual integrity.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 59, 3, 17, 17, 'which is hypocrisy', 'Connection of Hypocrisy and Wisdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in both passages. Luke warns against the ''leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy,'' while James describes wisdom from above as being ''without hypocrisy.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 40, 16, 6, 12, 'leaven of the Pharisees', 'Leaven of the Pharisees', 'Both passages emphasize the warning against the ''leaven of the Pharisees.'' This connection highlights the importance of recognizing hypocrisy and false teachings in religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 41, 8, 15, 21, 'leaven of the Pharisees', 'Leaven of the Pharisees', 'Both passages emphasize the warning against the ''leaven of the Pharisees,'' highlighting the theme of hypocrisy and misunderstanding among Jesus'' followers. The disciples'' confusion about bread reflects their failure to grasp the deeper spiritual lesson Jesus is teaching.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 42, 12, 56, 56, 'leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy', 'Hypocrisy and Discernment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in both passages. In Luke 12:1, Jesus warns against the ''leaven of the Pharisees, which is hypocrisy,'' while in Luke 12:56, he calls the people ''hypocrites'' for failing to discern the signs of the times.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 1, 12, 7, 17, 17, 'trode one upon another', 'Crowd Dynamics and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of crowds trampling individuals. In Luke, the multitude treads upon one another, while in 2 Kings, the people trod upon the appointed lord, leading to his death. This connection highlights the dangers of being overwhelmed by the masses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 41, 4, 22, 22, NULL, 'Revelation of Hidden Truths', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that hidden things will ultimately be revealed. They share similar phrasing about nothing being covered or hid that will not be made known.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 42, 8, 17, 17, 'neither hid, that shall not be known', 'Revelation of Hidden Truths', 'Both passages emphasize the inevitability of hidden things being revealed. The similar phrasing about what is ''hid'' and ''known'' reinforces this theme of disclosure.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 47, 5, 10, 10, 'nothing covered, that shall not be revealed', 'Revelation and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the inevitability of revelation and accountability. Luke 12:2 states that nothing hidden will be known, while 2 Corinthians 5:10 discusses appearing before Christ''s judgment seat for actions done in the body.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 21, 12, 14, 14, 'neither hid, that shall not be known', 'Revelation and Judgment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the revelation of hidden things and the judgment of secret actions. Luke 12:2 speaks of what is covered being revealed, while Ecclesiastes 12:14 states that God will bring every secret thing into judgment.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 40, 10, 26, 33, 'for there is nothing covered, that shall not be revealed', 'Revelation of Hidden Truths', 'Both passages emphasize that nothing hidden will remain concealed. This connection highlights the importance of speaking truthfully and boldly, as well as the value of individuals in God''s eyes.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 46, 4, 5, 5, 'nothing covered, that shall not be revealed', 'Revelation of Hidden Things', 'This connection highlights the theme of revelation, as both passages emphasize that hidden things will be brought to light. Luke 12:2 states that nothing covered will be revealed, while 1 Corinthians 4:5 speaks of bringing to light hidden things of darkness.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 2, 45, 2, 16, 16, 'nothing covered, that shall not be revealed', 'Revelation of Secrets', 'Both passages emphasize the revelation of hidden truths. Luke 12:2 states that nothing covered will be revealed, while Romans 2:16 speaks of God judging the secrets of men, indicating a future unveiling of what is concealed.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 3, 40, 10, 27, 27, 'spoken in darkness shall be heard in the light', 'Connection of Proclamation and Secrecy', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between speaking in darkness and proclaiming in light. They highlight the idea that private messages will be made public, urging followers to share what they have learned.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 3, 21, 10, 20, 20, 'spoken in darkness shall be heard', 'Speech and Its Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that spoken words, whether in private or public, will ultimately be revealed. Luke 12:3 speaks of what is spoken in darkness being heard in the light, while Ecclesiastes 10:20 warns that thoughts and words in secret will be disclosed.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 3, 40, 12, 36, 36, 'whatsoever ye have spoken in darkness', 'Accountability for Words', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of words spoken, highlighting that they will be revealed or accounted for. Luke 12:3 speaks of words spoken in darkness being heard in the light, while Matthew 12:36 mentions giving account for every idle word.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 3, 21, 10, 12, 13, 'whatsoever ye have spoken', 'Words and Their Consequences', 'This connection highlights the contrast between wise and foolish speech. Both passages emphasize the impact of words, with Luke focusing on their eventual revelation and Ecclesiastes on the nature of speech itself.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 3, 18, 24, 14, 15, 'in darkness shall be heard in the light', 'Light and Darkness Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between actions done in darkness and their eventual revelation. Luke speaks of what is hidden being proclaimed in the light, while Job describes the wickedness of those who act under the cover of night.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 12, 3, 65, 1, 14, 15, 'whatsoever ye have spoken in darkness', 'Judgment and Ungodly Deeds', 'Both passages emphasize the revelation of hidden words and deeds. Luke speaks of what is spoken in darkness being revealed, while Jude discusses the judgment of ungodly deeds and speeches.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
